Thanks for sharing your Prolific ID! How can I support you today?
I've been at work for a while now and we're overloaded, and not being able to do all the work is leading me to a fairly high level of stress.
I understand that's difficult; feeling overwhelmed can be really challenging. What specific tasks are causing you the most stress?

My job is very variable. I work with several teams and our workload depends on the requests they make. There are times when requests come from several teams at the same time and the response we give must be as fast as possible.
It sounds like you're feeling pressured by the unpredictability and urgency. How do you usually cope when the workload spikes?
I usually give priority to getting the work teams up and running so that nothing is left standing and then process all the results.
That makes sense; you’re trying to keep things moving. Do you find this approach helps reduce your stress, or does it create more pressure?

It usually helps, but sometimes the equipment fails and I need to work with them to resolve it, which makes me anxious because while I'm dealing with these problems I'm not dealing with the rest of the equipment.
I can see how that would create anxiety, feeling torn between tasks. What strategies have you tried to manage that anxiety when issues arise?
I try to ask my colleagues for help to take care of the equipment that I cannot take care of while I try to solve the problems.
That's a great strategy, reaching out for support can really help. How do your colleagues typically respond when you ask for help?
Normally good, we work well together, but sometimes they are also overworked and can't help me and I have to deal with everything.
That sounds frustrating; it’s tough when everyone’s stretched thin. How do you feel when you’re in that situation, having to manage everything alone?
quite oversaturated and stressed, and without seeing that I am running out of time to be able to solve everything
I understand that's overwhelming, feeling like time is slipping away. Have you considered setting boundaries or prioritizing tasks differently during those high-pressure times?

That's what I try to do, I prioritize what I think needs more attention, but sometimes users ask us to prioritize their own work due to company emergencies and for me that sometimes causes more stress, especially when it's work that takes a long time.
That sounds really challenging, especially with competing demands. How do you usually communicate your limits or concerns to users when those situations arise?
I usually tell them that there is a lot of work and that I will do everything possible, but I also feel that pressure from them that only makes me more anxious.
It’s understandable to feel that pressure; it can be really tough to manage. Have you thought about ways to express your capacity limits while still validating their urgency?
Yes, I already do it, and if it is very urgent, I end up wasting my free time to get the work done.
I see how that could lead to burnout, sacrificing your free time. How do you feel about setting clearer boundaries with your time to protect your well-being?

Thanks for sharing your Prolific ID! How can I support you today?
I have questions about stress and how can I mange it?
I understand that stress can be overwhelming. What specific situations are triggering your stress?
family members who are drug users and dont work and take advantage of my family
It sounds like you're feeling frustrated and helpless about your family's situation. How does this impact your own well-being?
it has been hard and I have been to the hospital for my stress
I'm really sorry to hear that you've reached that point. That must have been a tough experience for you. What do you think contributes most to your stress in these family dynamics?
the fact that we can not hold accountability to them and when we try to talk about it they attack with words and shouting
I understand that's difficult to navigate, especially when communication feels hostile. Have you found any strategies that help you cope during these confrontations?
yes I pray to my higher power and I go outdoors for a few hours and listen to music
Those sound like healthy coping mechanisms! It's great that you have those outlets. How do you feel after spending time outdoors and listening to music?
nature has a way of helping me feel better and fresh air is soothing and I do not think as much
It sounds like nature offers you a valuable escape and relief from stress. What else do you enjoy doing that brings you peace?
If I have the chance I go fishing and play some games
Fishing and gaming both sound like wonderful ways to unwind and find joy. How do those activities help you connect with yourself?
I have a good following in the gaming community and others value my friendship
That’s really heartwarming to hear! Feeling valued in your community can be uplifting. How does that support impact your overall emotional well-being?
it feels good and I feel a purpose and my new friends are like family to me
That sense of purpose and connection is so important! It sounds like your gaming friends really enrich your life. How do you nurture those friendships?
I like to keep in touch with them and get together and game
It’s wonderful that you actively maintain those connections! Spending time together must strengthen those bonds. How do those gaming sessions make you feel?
I feel really good and the challenges are a good way to get the team together
It's great that challenges bring you all closer together! That sense of teamwork can be really rewarding. Do you find those experiences help you cope with stress in other areas of your life?
Yes I know that I can go to my friends and have the support I need and talk about things
That support system sounds invaluable! Having friends to talk to can really lighten the emotional load. What topics do you usually discuss with them when you need support?
mostly family stuff and chats about work
It's good that you have a safe space to share those concerns. Talking about family and work can be so relieving. How do they typically respond to what you're going through?
test
